<div class=Section1>
<p>
<h1 align=center style='text-align:center'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Verdana","sans-serif";color:red'>Letter to a prisoner</span></h1>

<p>
<h1 align=center style='text-align:center'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Verdana","sans-serif";color:red'>Coarseness of life, the
unhappiness of prison, and prayer </span></h1>

<p>
<h1 align=center style='text-align:center'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Verdana","sans-serif";color:red'>Mary of Egypt Shows Us How to
Repent<br>
How to Cultivate a Repentant Spirit</span></h1>

<p>
<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'><b><i><span style='font-size:
14.0pt;text-transform:uppercase;layout-grid-mode:line'>&nbsp;</span></i></b></p>
<p class=MsoNormal>Priest Seraphim Holland PO 37 , McKinney TX 75070 </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>April 5/18/2016 Monday after the Sunday of St Mary of Egypt.
In a week, Holy Monday! </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>Dear in Christ _____: </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>I lament that you are so far away! I am working harder and
harder, and do not even have a job right now (my wife wants me to get back to
it, but I am all jumbled up, and although I do not like the poverty, I like the
breathing room. I always have something to do - services every day this week).
I want to find the time to come and see you, and Billy too. This will be an
overnight trip. It is hard to juggle all the plates. The system is really
messing with____. The chaplains there say that Orthodoxy is &quot;under the umbrella
of Roman Catholicism&quot;, so heб HAS access to services in his &quot;faith
group&quot;. Says who? Evidently the Roman Catholics. I need to get an official
letter that rebuts their position. I have no idea quite how to go about this. He
is hoping to get back to ____. I hope that you can get to ___ or ___. I would
see you twice a month. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>I really got dinged about my letter writing incompetency at ____
recently. People get really offended. I lose letters. I cannot figure out how
to write a short letter! I am trying hard to write replies without a day or two
of receiving a letter, and am working through my backlog - those I can find. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>I understand your predicament. You can be alone if you do
not fall into depression. We are social creatures. Hopefully, you can find
someone who is a kindred spirit. I hate mundane things. I hate the coarseness
of life. There is a lot of that in prison. It is good to guard yourself, but
you must also guard yourself from cynicism and judgment. When you see somebody
in a bad way, secretly pray for them. I think this will help. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>Ancient Faith Radio is great, but it is INTERNET radio. I am
not aware of Orthodox programs on the regular radio. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>I would love to be able to talk to youб in the flesh, but
this is quite hard to do. I will be happy to be a sounding board, and give
advice, if I know anything. I suppose we must make do, with letters. Since the
new me replies more quickly (and usually via jpay) you may get a reply in less
than a week. I do need to check my PO box more often though. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>I remember ___. He was very quiet. I believe he is Roman
Catholic. I never got a good read on his intentions. Anybody can come to our services,
but I want to be of service to those who also want to come to the Orthodox
faith. ___ is a catechumen. He is still pretty wild, but he is making some
progress. бI need somebody like you and ___, to help be leaders of the group.б
I have a lotб that come, but I have only two baptized Orthodox.</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>б____ had confession and communion for the first time in,
maybe 2 or 3 years? He was very happy, and so was I .б His battles are
emotional. As you know, the mind is a tough place to be. бThe other Orthodox
guy was a businessman, successful, never did a criminal thing in his life, and
then BAM! A stupid decision. He communed for the first time, since I knew him
He speaks 4 languages fluently. I am just telling you all this, because, I
dunno, I need a sounding board too, and you understand about the unhappiness in
prison, andб in some ways, I do too. If I did not pray, it would consume me. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>I have finished replying to everything in your letter, and
will close with a sermon about St Mary of Egypt. I do not rememberб if you have
her life. I will try to print it and send it. Write me with any question, any
observation. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>God bless you! </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>This document is at: </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><a
href="https://www.orthodox.net//full-voice/prison-ministry-letters_2016-04-18+coarseness-of-life-the-unhappiness-of-prison-and-prayer+mary-of-egypt-shows-us-how-to-repent.html">https://www.orthodox.net//full-voice/prison-ministry-letters_2016-04-18+coarseness-of-life-the-unhappiness-of-prison-and-prayer+mary-of-egypt-shows-us-how-to-repent.html</a></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><a
href="https://www.orthodox.net//full-voice/prison-ministry-letters_2016-04-18+coarseness-of-life-the-unhappiness-of-prison-and-prayer+mary-of-egypt-shows-us-how-to-repent.doc">https://www.orthodox.net//full-voice/prison-ministry-letters_2016-04-18+coarseness-of-life-the-unhappiness-of-prison-and-prayer+mary-of-egypt-shows-us-how-to-repent.doc</a></p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<h1 align=center style='text-align:center'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Verdana","sans-serif";color:red'>Mary of Egypt Shows Us How to
Repent<br>
How to Cultivate a Repentant Spirit</span></h1>

<p>
<h2 align=center style='text-align:center'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Verdana","sans-serif";color:red'>Sunday of St Mary of Egypt. Fifth
Sunday of Great Lent </span></h2>

ly:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[ii]</span></span></span></a>
from the time of her repentance for her to no longer be plagued with carnal
thoughts and imaginings and drinking songs and desire for wine and for meat and
for all of the things that she had before. It took her 17 years to be cleansed
of those desires, and she wasnЖt indulging in any of them; she was in the
desert and seeing no people whatsoever, eating almost nothing, being burned by
the sun and frozen by the frost. And yet it took 17 years, which included such
things as: lying on the ground for a day and a night, begging the Lord to
remove from her these thoughts of songs and these desires and these carnal
imaginings and, as the life says, a desire for embraces. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
But the pivotal thing was her conscience turned. And after her repentance she
still thought of herself as dust and ashes and as sinful Mary. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
So this gives us an indication, brothers and sisters, of how we should live. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>What we have to do is this: We have to cultivate in
ourselves the knowledge of whatЖs wrong with us, that there are things that we
just donЖt do right, and there are things we do that are wrong. We must
cultivate this idea in ourselves. The world doesnЖt like us to do this because
itЖs just <i>too hard</i> to do, so the world labels it as sometimes poor self-esteem
or as not having faith. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
Saint Mary had great faith such that when she prayed she was above the ground a
forearmЖs length. But she also was well aware of her sinful life and never
forgot it, not a day, not a moment. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
ItЖs said of Saint Peter the Apostle that he desired, when he was going to be
crucified he asked to be crucified upside down because he didnЖt feel he was
worthy to be crucified in the same way that his Lord was crucified. This is the
same Peter, of course, who denied the Lord three times before His <br>
crucifixion during His trial. He never forgot that. Even though the Lord
cleansed him of that sin and restored him and told him to фfeed My lambs, feed
My sheepц<a href="#_edn3" name="_ednref3" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[iii]</span></span></span></a>.
And Peter of course did all those things, fed the lambs and fed the sheep and
became a great apostle. But he never forgot that sin. <br>
<br>
</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>Jude, one of the sons of Joseph the Betrothed, and an apostle,
never forgot that he sinned against the Lord when Joseph wanted to divide up
his inheritance and divide it four ways for four sons, Ruben and Jude and James
and Jesus; and Jude didnЖt want to do it. He said our Lord was not JosephЖs
son. So he wanted to divide it three ways. So James (he was one of the seventy
Apostles, and the first bishop of Jerusalem) offered to have his portion be
given to the Lord. Jude repented of that sin many times over, and never forgot
it. He referred to himself as Jude the brother of James<a href="#_edn4"
name="_ednref4" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[iv]</span></span></span></a>,
even though he was one of the twelve apostles, and his brother was not. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>This is the kind of feeling we should have to cultivate about
ourselves, brothers and sisters: Humility, бso that our conscience can turn. <br>
<br>
</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>Now in our case our conscience is going to have to turn
every day, so we must cultivate it with silence, with prayer, with fasting,
with reading of the Holy Scriptures and holy things, with long services. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal><b>Short services donЖt cut it, really.</b> Oh, theyЖre
helpful, but long services really help. And if you donЖt know this, take me on
my word and try it. It will be hard. Sometimes it will be boring. Sometimes you
will think, жWow, IЖm just thinking about everything but the services.Ж But if
you go to long services for a long time, it really changes you, it kind of
warms you, and it shapes you. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
What things are there that kill our conscience? Well, how about responding to
five hundred text messages a day on your smart phone? I think we should call
them stupid phones. IЖm not so sure this technology is good for our souls. Oh,
yes, it can be used in a good way. But now we are flooded by stuff all the
time. How about watching a lot of TV? How about reading magazines that are
frivolous or even sinful? How about gossip, pride and indulgence of our
desires? The list is very long, actually, of the things that kill the
conscience, compared to the list of things that enable the conscience to turn.
ItЖs really a very small list of things that enables the conscience to be
changed and a long list that can kill the conscience. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
We must cultivate in ourselves, brothers and sisters, all things that can turn
our conscience and make us aware. <br>
<br>
Saint Mary of Egypt lived 17 years of heedless sin. It never crossed her mind
during that time that she was sinning. She just did it. She did terrible
things. She edited her story, she told Abba Zosimas, because she just couldnЖt
bear to tell him all the things that she had done. But she was not ashamed of
any of them until her time of repentance, and then she had changed so
magnificently. <br>
<br>
</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>Let me read you one thing also that applies to this from
matins. I read things from matins as often as possible in this sermon<a
href="#_edn5" name="_ednref5" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[v]</span></span></span></a>
because, to be honest, the majority of my flock never hears matins, and I think
that itЖs the most important service that you can attend in the week. Part of
that is because it comes in our usage after Vespers so that there is a time, of
softening, getting you ready for deeper prayer<a href="#_edn6" name="_ednref6"
title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[vi]</span></span></span></a>.
It is very hard to pray walking through the door. Also, the content of matins
is so beautifully, intricately theological. But itЖs not just theological;
thereЖs a warmth to the prayers of Matins that is truly amazing. Whether it is
said in the morning (unless it is abbreviated almost beyond recognition) or in
the evening, it does not matter. Truly, this is a service that I lament that so
much of my flock does not experience. ItЖs very, very important. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
The following is from one of the sessional hymns during the canon, after the
third ode. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:0in;margin-right:.4in;margin-bottom:0in;
margin-left:.4in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify'><span
style='font-family:"Verdana","sans-serif"'>фI am held fast in the mire of sin,
and there is no strength or courage in me; the tempest of my trespasses has
overwhelmed me. Look upon me, 0 Virgin, I entreat Thee, for thou has borne the
Word Who alone loves mankind. Deliver me from every sin, from all the passions
that destroy my soul, and from every ill inflicted by the enemy, that I may
sing with joy. Intercede with thy Son and God, 0 Undefiled, that remission of
transgressions may been given to those who in faith take refuge beneath thy
protection.ц </span></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
<i>фI am held fast in the mire of sin.ц</i> ThatЖs what Saint Mary tells about
herself when she repented. And for those 17 years that she was held fast in
that mire, she felt it deeply. And after she was delivered from it and lived
more like an angel than a human being, she still remembered. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
We must cultivate in ourselves this feeling. Ask yourself, do you feel this
about yourself? Do you really feel deeply that you are held fast in the mire of
sin, that there is no strength in you, or courage in you? This is not to feel
absolutely defeated, this is not to say I canЖt accomplish anything. This is to
say I canЖt accomplish anything <i>without help</i>. We must have this humility
about ourselves. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
If we consider ourselves to be held fast in the mire of бsin - itЖs true
whether you believe it or not - then we will make progress, because we will beg
the Lord for help. We will beg the most Holy Theotokos to pray for us. We will
beg our Guardian Angel to guard and keep us and the saints to intercede for us,
and we will change. And when God whispers to us in those words that cannot be
uttered from the Holy Spirit<a href="#_edn7" name="_ednref7" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[vii]</span></span></span></a>,
we will react to them, we will understand and then and we will change. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal><i>But we must have the right disposition.</i> And the right
disposition is to say I am a terrible sinners, the worst of all sinners and yet
God will save me by His mercy. We must cultivate this feeling. Saint Mary had
it, and we should be in awe of her repentance. But not believe for a moment
that her repentance is only a <i>unique</i> experience, a unique event not to
be repeated. No, it should be repeated every day, with us too. God calls us to
this level of repentance also. <br>
<br>
</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>So cultivate this idea in your heart, brothers and sisters. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>ItЖs not easy to do. Like I said, there are things you can
do. Prayer and fasting, giving yourself more time for prayer, the Jesus prayer,
is pretty much essential. Things you shouldnЖt do: Watching television and
foolish books and gossip and all the rest. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal><br>
But primarily, with all these things that you should do and shouldnЖt do, you
must put your trust in God completely, and thatЖs what Saint Mary did and
thatЖs what all the saints did. And the reason we are mediocre is because we
donЖt do this completely. </p>
<p class=MsoNormal>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>So may God help us to completely trust in God. <br>
<br>
</p>
<p class=MsoNormal>фThe blessing of the Lord be upon you through His grace and
love for mankind, always now and ever and unto the ages of ages. Amen.ц<a
href="#_edn8" name="_ednref8" title=""><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[viii]</span></span></span></a></p>
<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='color:black'>&nbsp;</span></p>
<div style='border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 1.0pt 0in'>

<p>
<p class=MsoBodyText style='border:none;padding:0in'><span style='font-size:
10.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>

<p>
<p class=MsoBodyText align=center style='text-align:center'><span
style='font-size:8.0pt'>Priest Seraphim Holland 2011.бббб </span></p>
<p class=MsoBodyText align=center style='text-align:center'><span
style='font-size:8.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
style='font-family:"Arial","sans-serif"'>This and other Orthodox materials are
available in from:</span></b><span style='font-family:"Arial","sans-serif"'> </span></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
style='font-family:"Arial","sans-serif"'><a href="https://www.orthodox.net//">St.
Nicholas Orthodox Church, McKinney, Texas</a></span></b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
style='font-family:"Arial","sans-serif"'>&nbsp;</span></b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText style='margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style='font-family:Symbol'>+<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span style='font-family:"Arial","sans-serif"'>Mailing
Address: Box 37, McKinney, TX 75070</span></b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText style='margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style='font-family:Symbol'>+<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span style='font-family:"Arial","sans-serif"'>Rectory Phone:
972/529-2754</span></b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText style='margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style='font-family:Symbol'>+<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span style='font-family:"Arial","sans-serif"'>Email: <a
href="mailto:seraphim@orthodox.net"><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif";
font-weight:normal'>seraphim@orthodox.net</span></a></span></b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText style='margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style='font-family:Symbol'>+<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span style='font-family:"Arial","sans-serif"'>Web Page: <a
href="https://www.orthodox.net//"><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif";
font-weight:normal'>https://www.orthodox.net/</span></a></span></b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText style='margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style='font-family:Symbol'>+<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span style='font-family:"Arial","sans-serif"'>Redeeming the
Time Blog:</span> </b><a href="https://www.orthodox.net//redeemingthetime/">https://www.orthodox.net//redeemingthetime/</a><b>
</b></p>
<p class=MsoBodyText align=center style='text-align:center'><span
style='font-size:8.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class=MsoBodyText>This homily is at: </p>
<p class=MsoBodyText><a
href="https://www.orthodox.net//sermons/great-lent-sunday-05_2011-04-09+mary-of-egypt-shows-us-how-to-repent+how-to-cultivate-a-repentanct-spirit.doc">https://www.orthodox.net//sermons/great-lent-sunday-05_2011-04-09+mary-of-egypt-shows-us-how-to-repent+how-to-cultivate-a-repentanct-spirit.doc</a></p>
<p class=MsoBodyText><a
href="https://www.orthodox.net//sermons/great-lent-sunday-05_2011-04-09+mary-of-egypt-shows-us-how-to-repent+how-to-cultivate-a-repentanct-spirit.html">https://www.orthodox.net//sermons/great-lent-sunday-05_2011-04-09+mary-of-egypt-shows-us-how-to-repent+how-to-cultivate-a-repentanct-spirit.html</a></p>
<p class=MsoBodyText>AUDIO: <a
href="https://www.orthodox.net//sermons/great-lent-sunday-05_2011-04-09+mary-of-egypt-shows-us-how-to-repent+how-to-cultivate-a-repentanct-spirit.mp3">https://www.orthodox.net//sermons/great-lent-sunday-05_2011-04-09+mary-of-egypt-shows-us-how-to-repent+how-to-cultivate-a-repentanct-spirit.mp3</a></p>
<p class=MsoBodyText>&nbsp;</p>
<p class=MsoBodyText align=center style='text-align:center'><a
href="http://www/.orthodox.net/redeemingthetime">http://www/.orthodox.net/redeemingthetime</a></p>
<p class=MsoBodyText align=center style='text-align:center'>Archive of <b>commentaries</b>:
<a href="https://www.orthodox.net//scripture">https://www.orthodox.net//scripture</a></p>
<p class=MsoBodyText align=center style='text-align:center'>Archive of <b>homilies</b>:
<a href="https://www.orthodox.net//sermons">https://www.orthodox.net//sermons</a></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText align=center style='text-align:center;text-indent:.5in'><b>&nbsp;</b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><b>To receive regular mailings of sermons, and
scriptural and services commentary and other things throughout the church year,
read our blog фRedeeming the Timeц (<a
href="https://www.orthodox.net//redeemingthetime">https://www.orthodox.net//redeemingthetime</a>).
You may also subscribe to the <a
href="http://orthodox.net/redeemingthetime/?feed=rss2">RSS Feed</a> or receive
its postings by <a
href="http://www.feedburner.com/fb/a/emailverifySubmit?feedId=1469611&amp;loc=en_US">email</a>.
</b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><b>&nbsp;</b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><b>Our parish Email list (<a
href="http://groups.google.com/group/saint-nicholas-orthodox-church">http://groups.google.com/group/saint-nicholas-orthodox-church</a>)
also has all the latest postings from our <a href="https://www.orthodox.net//">website</a>
and <a href="https://www.orthodox.net//redeemingthetime">blog</a>; everyone is
welcome to join. </b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><b>&nbsp;</b></p>
<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><b><span style='font-size:8.0pt'>All
rights reserved.б Please use this material in any edifying reason. We ask that
you contact St. Nicholas if you wish to distribute it in any way.б We grant
permission to post this text, if completely intact only, including this
paragraph and the URL of the text, to any electronic mailing list, church
bulletin, web page or blog.</span></b></p>
<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'><b><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></b></p>
</div>

<p>
<div><br clear=all>

<p>
<hr align=left size=1 width="33%">

<p>
<div id=edn1>

<p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[i]</span></span></span></a>
ф<span class=reader>And let no one think (continues St. Sophronius) that I have
had the audacity to write untruth or doubt this great marvel --may I never lie
about holy things! If there do happen to be people who, after reading this
record, do not believe it, may the Lord have mercy on them because, reflecting
on the weakness of human nature, they consider impossible these wonderful
things accomplished by holy people.</span>ц (From the Life of St Mary of Egypt,
read on the fifth Thursday of Great Lent - <b><a
href="https://www.orthodox.net//saints/mary-of-egypt.html">https://www.orthodox.net//saints/mary-of-egypt.html</a>
)</b></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText>&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<p>
<div id=edn2>

<p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[ii]</span></span></span></a>
See фThe Life of Mary of Egypt by the numbersц ы <a
href="https://www.orthodox.net//journal/2011-04-05+life-of-saint-mary-of-egpyt-by-the-numbers.html">https://www.orthodox.net//journal/2011-04-05+life-of-saint-mary-of-egpyt-by-the-numbers.html</a>
and <a
href="https://www.orthodox.net//journal/2011-04-05+life-of-saint-mary-of-egpyt-by-the-numbers.doc">https://www.orthodox.net//journal/2011-04-05+life-of-saint-mary-of-egpyt-by-the-numbers.doc</a></p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText>&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<p>
<div id=edn3>

<p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[iii]</span></span></span></a>
John 21:15-17 фSo when they had dined, Jesus saith to Simon Peter, Simon, <i>son</i>
of Jonas, lovest thou me more than these? He saith unto him, Yea, Lord; thou
knowest that I have affection for thee. He saith unto him, Feed my lambs.б
(16)б He saith to him again the second time, Simon, <i>son</i> of Jonas, lovest
thou me? He saith unto him, Yea, Lord; thou knowest that I have affection for
thee. He saith unto him, Feed my sheep.б (17)б He saith unto him the third
time, Simon, <i>son</i> of Jonas, hast thou affection for me? Peter was grieved
because he said unto him the third time, hast thou affection for me? And he
said unto him, Lord, thou knowest all things; thou knowest that I have
affection for thee. Jesus saith unto him, Feed my sheep.</p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText>&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<p>
<div id=edn4>

<p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[iv]</span></span></span></a>
For example: фJude, the servant of Jesus Christ, and brother of James, to them
that are sanctified by God the Father, and preserved in Jesus Christ, <i>and</i>
called:б <span style='font-size:8.0pt'>(2)</span>б Mercy unto you, and peace,
and love, be multiplied.ц <span style='font-size:8.0pt'>(Jude 1:1-2 KJV)</span></p>
</div>

<p>
<div id=edn5>

<p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[v]</span></span></span></a>
It is our custom at St Nicholas, as often as possible to give a short homily
between Vespers and Matins, during our vigil service for Saturday night. Some
people leave after Vespers and never hear the matins service. </p>
</div>

<p>
<div id=edn6>

<p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[vi]</span></span></span></a>
Matins is just as effective is served IN ITS ENTIRETY in the morning, before
liturgy. Morning is a wonderful time to pray, when our thoughts are more
collected. A very short matins, with much of the фmeatц taken out of it, served
in the morning, is not so useful. We would prosper much more as a people if
this unfortunate practice, of serving services that have the name, but not the
content that is so beneficial to the soul. </p>
</div>

<p>
<div id=edn7>

<p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[vii]</span></span></span></a>
Romans 8:26 Likewise the Spirit also helpeth our infirmities: for we know not
what we should pray for as we ought: but the Spirit itself maketh intercession
for us with groanings which cannot be uttered.</p>
</div>

<p>
<div id=edn8>

<p>
<p class=MsoEndnoteText><a href="#_ednref8" name="_edn8" title=""><span
class=MsoEndnoteReference><span class=MsoEndnoteReference><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>[viii]</span></span></span></a>
This is the last blessing said by the priest at the end of Vespers, just prior
to the beginning of the Six Psalms of Matins. </p>
</div>

<p>
</div>

<p>

<p>
